### login Utility
```typescript
// Problem: Complex browser dependencies
// Solution: Simplified global mocking

describe("login", () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    Object.defineProperty(global, "window", {
      value: {
        location: { href: "https://example.com" },
        setTimeout: vi.fn((callback) => { callback(); return 1; }),
        Check24: { uliloginlayer: { open: vi.fn() } },
        C24App: { triggerUnifiedLogin: vi.fn() },
      },
      writable: true,
    });
  });

  it("calls Check24 uliloginlayer.open", () => {
    const { login } = require("./login");
    login();
    expect(global.window.Check24.uliloginlayer.open).toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
});
```

## Best Practices

1. **Always investigate actual behavior** before fixing tests
2. **Document why expectations are what they are**
3. **Use function existence tests** for complex cases
4. **Simplify mocks** when possible
5. **Clean up after tests** to avoid side effects
6. **Focus on testable aspects** rather than implementation details

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

### ❌ Blindly Changing Expectations
```typescript
// BAD: Changing test without understanding why
it("handles input", () => {
  expect(function(input)).toBe("new expectation"); // Why?
});
```

### ❌ Over-Complex Mocking
```typescript
// BAD: Complex mocking when simple approach works
describe("utility", () => {
  it("over-complex test", () => {
    // Too many mocks, hard to maintain
  });
});
```

### ❌ Testing Implementation Details
```typescript
// BAD: Testing how function works instead of what it does
it("calls internal function", () => {
  // Don't test internal implementation
});
```

